{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505208"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:27:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:27:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2418"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2418"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0,0.03,0.04,0.9]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2418"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59470"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2418"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2418"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44876"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1465"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"1858"},{"type":"tags","id":"2451"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4378"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12800"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1812"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1885"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7454"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42487"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43146"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59470"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 39-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-hour history of bright red vaginal bleeding at 36 weeks gestation. This is her fourth pregnancy, with three previous uncomplicated vaginal deliveries. She had a similar episode of bleeding two days ago that resolved spontaneously. Her antenatal care has been uncomplicated except for a low-lying posterior placenta noted on her 20-week morphology scan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed and in pain. Her pulse rate is 130/min, blood pressure 80/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, and SpO2 96% on room air. Speculum examination reveals blood pooling in the posterior fornix. Cardiotocography shows a fetal heart rate of 110/min with late decelerations. Bedside ultrasound confirms cephalic presentation with the placenta 2 cm from the cervix and an incidental retroplacental haematoma. Despite a 500 mL crystalloid bolus via a large-bore cannula, she remains haemodynamically unstable. Blood has been cross-matched.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Observe for six hours in hospital","Discharge home with follow-up","Administer magnesium sulfate","Proceed to immediate vaginal delivery","Proceed to immediate caesarean delivery"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a life-threatening antepartum haemorrhage with features of both placenta praevia (low-lying placenta) and placental abruption (retroplacental haematoma). The combination of maternal instability (tachycardia, hypotension) and fetal compromise (late decelerations) makes this an obstetric emergency requiring immediate delivery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProceed to immediate caesarean delivery\u003C/strong\u003E is the only appropriate option given the presence of placenta praevia, maternal instability, and fetal compromise. The presence of both placental complications significantly increases the risk of catastrophic haemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObserve for six hours in hospital\u003C/strong\u003E would be dangerous in this scenario. Observation is only appropriate for small amounts of bleeding in a haemodynamically stable mother with reassuring fetal status.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDischarge home with follow-up\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate and potentially catastrophic given the active bleeding and unstable maternal and fetal condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister magnesium sulfate\u003C/strong\u003E would be contraindicated as it is a tocolytic that could worsen bleeding by preventing uterine contractions. Tocolysis has no role in antepartum haemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProceed to immediate vaginal delivery\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated due to the presence of placenta praevia, which is an absolute indication for caesarean delivery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile 90% of placentas identified as low-lying at 20 weeks will migrate to a normal position by the third trimester, this patient\u0027s placenta remains low-lying at 36 weeks. The combination of placenta praevia and abruption, along with the maternal and fetal compromise, makes this a surgical emergency requiring immediate caesarean delivery.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Antepartum haemorrhage with maternal instability and fetal compromise requires immediate caesarean delivery.","The combination of placenta praevia and placental abruption is particularly dangerous and requires urgent intervention.","90% of placentas identified as low-lying at 20 weeks will migrate to a normal position by the third trimester."],"references":["Ananth CV, Lavery JA, Vintzileos AM, et al. Severe placental abruption: clinical definition and associations with maternal complications. Am J Obstet Gynecol 2016; 214:272.e1. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26393335/","Mei Y, Lin Y. Clinical significance of primary symptoms in women with placental abruption. J Matern Fetal Neonatal Med 2018; 31:2446. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28629246/","Osoti, A. Placenta Previa and Placenta Abrution. In: FIGO [online]. 2021; Accessed 31/10/22. Available at: https://www.glowm.com/article/heading/vol-10--common-obstetric-conditions--placenta-previa-and-placenta-abruption/id/413763#.Y18oyC0RoUE"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44876"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2418"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44876"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-07T20:43:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-08T12:11:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2418"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59470"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name"